{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019BKMfH2Gz5ajKFuM4aorq8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So PVCs are Bound and there's data in /data/db. The MongoDB data is already there from when the mongod started running (it started fresh, initialized the replica set). But no admin user was created.\n\nThe issue is that with `--auth` and a keyfile, MongoDB's localhost exception is still active for the first user creation - but ONLY before any users are created. The question is whether the localhost exception is active now.\n\nWait, I re-read the error: `MongoServerError: command createUser requires authentication`. This is strange if no users exist. \nLet me reconsider the MongoDB auth behavior. With `--auth` enabled and no users in the admin database, the localhost exception should allow creating the first admin user without authentication when connecting locally. But when using a keyFile, it implicitly enables auth, and the localhost exception should still be active before any users exist. The error message saying `createUser requires authentication` is puzzling - either the localhost exception isn't activating, or there's already a user despite the UserNotFound logs. The keyFile might be affecting how the localhost exception works in this replica set context. So the localhost exception only works before the replica set is initiated with members, which means I can't use it now. I need to either temporarily disable auth to create the admin user, or find another way to authenticate. The cleanest approach for Kubernetes would be restarting the StatefulSet without the auth flags to bootstrap the initial user, then re-enabling them.\n\nActually, I can use the `__system` internal replication user from the keyfile itself—I should extract the keyfile content from the secret and authenticate as `__system` in the local database to create the admin user.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence